# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: battery-storage-grid
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] A battery pack built together with a BMS with an external communication data bus is a smart battery pack.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] A smart battery pack must be charged by a smart battery charger.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] Battery thermal management systems can be either passive or active, and the cooling medium can either be air, liquid, or some form of phase change.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] Air cooling is advantageous in its simplicity.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] Such systems can be passive, relying only on the convection of the surrounding air, or active, using fans for airflow.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] Commercially, the Honda Insight and Toyota Prius both use active air cooling of their battery systems.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] The major disadvantage of air cooling is its inefficiency.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] Large amounts of power must be used to operate the cooling mechanism, far more than active liquid cooling.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] The additional components of the cooling mechanism also add weight to the BMS, reducing the efficiency of batteries used for transportation.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] Liquid cooling has a higher natural cooling potential than air cooling as liquid coolants tend to have higher thermal conductivities than air.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] The batteries can either be directly submerged in the coolant or the coolant can flow through the BMS without directly contacting the battery.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] Indirect cooling has the potential to create large thermal gradients across the BMS due to the increased length of the cooling channels.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] This can be reduced by pumping the coolant faster through the system, creating a tradeoff between pumping speed and thermal consistency.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] The central controller of a BMS communicates internally with its hardware operating at a cell level, or externally with high level hardware such as laptops or an HMI.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] Low-voltage centralized BMSes mostly do not have any internal communications.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] Distributed or modular BMSes must use some low-level internal cell–controller (modular architecture) or controller–controller (distributed architecture) communication.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] These types of communications are difficult, especially for high-voltage systems.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] The problem is the voltage shift between cells.The first cell ground signal may be hundreds of volts higher than the other cell ground signal.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] Apart from software protocols, there are two known ways of hardware communication for voltage shifting systems, optical-isolator and wireless communication.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] Another restriction for internal communications is the maximum number of cells.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] For modular architecture, most hardware is limited to a maximum of 255 nodes.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] For high-voltage systems the seeking time of all cells is another restriction, limiting minimum bus speeds and losing some hardware options.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] The cost of modular systems is important, because it may be comparable to the cell price.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] To bypass power limitations of existing USB cables due to heat from electric current, communication protocols implemented in mobile phone chargers for negotiating an elevated voltage have been developed, the most widely used of which are Qualcomm Quick Charge and MediaTek Pump Express.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] More recently, the USB Power Delivery standard aims for a universal negotiation protocol across devices of up to 240 watts.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] A BMS may also feature a precharge system allowing a safe way to connect the battery to different loads and eliminating the excessive inrush currents to load capacitors.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] The connection to loads is normally controlled through electromagnetic relays called contactors.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] The precharge circuit can be either power resistors connected in series with the loads until the capacitors are charged.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] Alternatively, a switched mode power supply connected in parallel to loads can be used to charge the voltage of the load circuit up to a level close enough to the battery voltage in to allow closing the contactors between the battery and load circuit.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] A BMS may have a circuit that can check whether a relay is already closed before recharging (due to welding for example) to prevent inrush currents from occurring.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] In order to maximize the battery's capacity, and to prevent localized under-charging or over-charging, the BMS may actively ensure that all the cells that compose the battery are kept at the same voltage or State of Charge, through balancing.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] Some chargers accomplish the balance by charging each cell independently.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] This is often performed by the BMS and not the charger (which typically provides only the bulk charge current, and does not interact with the pack at the cell-group level), e.g., e-bike and hoverboard chargers.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] In this method, the BMS will request a lower charge current (such as EV batteries), or will shut-off the charging input (typical in portable electronics) through the use of transistor circuitry while balancing is in effect (to prevent over-charging cells).
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] Centralized BMSs are the most economical, least expandable, and are plagued by a multitude of wires.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] Distributed BMSs are the most expensive, simplest to install, and offer the cleanest assembly.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] Modular BMSes offer a compromise of the features and problems of the other two topologies.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] In the case of electric or hybrid vehicles, the BMS is only a subsystem and cannot work as a stand-alone device.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] It must communicate with at least a charger (or charging infrastructure), a load, thermal management and emergency shutdown subsystems.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] Therefore, in a good vehicle design the BMS is tightly integrated with those subsystems.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] Some small mobile applications (such as medical equipment carts, motorized wheelchairs, scooters, and forklifts) often have external charging hardware, however the on board BMS must still have tight design integration with the external charger.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-management-system] Various battery balancing methods are in use, some of them based on state of charge theory.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] A **battery energy storage system** (**BESS**), **battery storage power station**, **battery energy grid storage** (**BEGS**) or **battery grid storage** is a type of energy storage technology that uses a group of batteries in the grid to store electrical energy.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Battery storage is the fastest responding dispatchable source of power on electric grids, and it is used to stabilise those grids, as battery storage can transition from standby to full power in under a second to deal with grid contingencies.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Battery energy storage systems are generally designed to deliver their full rated power for durations ranging from 1 to 4 hours, with emerging technologies extending this to longer durations to meet evolving grid demands.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Battery storage can be used for short-term peak power demand and for ancillary services, such as providing operating reserve and frequency control to minimize the chance of power outages.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] They are often installed at, or close to, other active or disused power stations and may share the same grid connection to reduce costs.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Since battery storage plants require no deliveries of fuel, are compact compared to generating stations and have no chimneys or large cooling systems, they can be rapidly installed and placed if necessary within urban areas, close to customer load, or even inside customer premises.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] As of 2021, the power and capacity of the largest individual battery storage system is an order of magnitude less than that of the largest pumped-storage power plants, the most common form of grid energy storage.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] For example, the Bath County Pumped Storage Station, the second largest in the world, can store 24 GWh of electricity and dispatch 3 GW while the first phase of Vistra Energy's Moss Landing Energy Storage Facility can store 1.2 GWh and dispatch 300 MW.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] However, grid batteries do not have to be large — a high number of smaller ones (often as hybrid power) can be widely deployed across a grid for greater redundancy and large overall capacity.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] By 2025, global power capacity was 267 GW with 610 GWh energy capacity.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] As of 2019, battery power storage is typically cheaper than open cycle gas turbine power for use up to two hours, and there was around 365 GWh of battery storage deployed worldwide, growing rapidly.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Levelized cost of storage (LCOS) has fallen rapidly.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] From 2014 to 2024, cost halving time was 4.1 years.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] The price was US$150 per MWh in 2020, and further reduced to US$117 by 2023.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Battery storage power plants and uninterruptible power supplies (UPS) are comparable in technology and function.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] However, battery storage power plants are larger.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] For safety and security, the actual batteries are housed in their own structures, like warehouses or containers.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] As with a UPS, one concern is that electrochemical energy is stored or emitted in the form of direct current (DC), while electric power networks are usually operated with alternating current (AC).
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] For this reason, additional inverters are needed to connect the battery storage power plants to the high voltage network.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] This kind of power electronics include gate turn-off thyristor, commonly used in high-voltage direct current (HVDC) transmission.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Various accumulator systems may be used depending on the power-to-energy ratio, the expected lifetime and the costs.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] In the 1980s, lead-acid batteries were used for the first battery-storage power plants.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] During the next few decades, nickel–cadmium, nickel-hydride and sodium–sulfur batteries were increasingly used.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Since 2010, more and more utility-scale battery storage plants rely on lithium-ion batteries, as a result of their fast cost decrease combined with increased energy and power, caused by the electric automotive industry, and they are now the main type used.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Batteries are becoming increasingly diverse, optimized for different aspects of customer requirements such as cost, safety or durability.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] A 4-hour flow vanadium redox battery at 175 MW / 700 MWh opened in 2024.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Lead-acid batteries are still used in small budget applications.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Most of the BESS systems are composed of securely sealed battery packs, which are electronically monitored and replaced once their performance falls below a given threshold.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Batteries suffer from cycle ageing, or deterioration caused by charge–discharge cycles.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] This deterioration is generally higher at high charging rates and higher depth of discharge.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] This aging causes a loss of performance (capacity or voltage decrease), overheating, and may eventually lead to critical failure (electrolyte leaks, fire, explosion).
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Sometimes battery storage power stations are built with flywheel storage power systems in order to conserve battery power.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Flywheels may handle rapid fluctuations better than older battery plants.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] BESS warranties typically include lifetime limits on energy throughput, expressed as number of charge–discharge cycles.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Lead-acid batteries, as a first-generation technology, are generally used in older BESS systems.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Some examples are 1.6 MW peak, 1.0 MW continuous battery was commissioned in 1997.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Compared to modern rechargeable batteries, lead-acid batteries have relatively low energy density.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Despite this, they are able to supply high surge currents.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] However, non-sealed lead-acid batteries produce hydrogen and oxygen from the aqueous electrolyte when overcharged.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] The water has to be refilled regularly to avoid damage to the battery; and, the inflammable gases have to be vented out to avoid explosion risks.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] However, this maintenance has a cost, and recent batteries such as Li-ion batteries do not have such an issue.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Lithium-ion batteries offer a long lifespan with minimal maintenance, high energy density, and low self-discharge, which makes them ideal for modern utility-scale BESS applications.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] A drawback of some types of lithium-ion batteries is fire safety, mostly ones containing cobalt.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] The number of BESS incidents has remained around 10–20 per year (mostly within the first 2–3 years of age), despite the large increase in number and size of BESS.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Failures occurred mostly in controls and balance of system, while 11% occurred in cells.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Examples of BESS fire accidents include individual modules in 23 battery farms in South Korea in 2017 to 2019, a Tesla Megapack in Geelong, the fire and subsequent explosion of a battery module in Arizona, and the cooling liquid short circuiting incidents and fire at the Moss Landing LG battery.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] This resulted in more research in recent years for mitigation measures for fire safety.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] By 2024, the lithium iron phosphate (LFP) battery has become another significant type for large storages due to the high availability of its components, longer lifetime and higher safety compared to nickel-based Li-ion chemistries.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] An LFP-based energy storage system that was installed in Paiyun Lodge on Mt.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Jade (Yushan) (the highest alpine lodge in Taiwan) and operated since 2016 without a safety incident.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Sodium-based batteries are another BESS technology.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Compared to lithium-ion batteries, sodium-ion batteries have somewhat lower cost, better safety characteristics, and similar power delivery characteristics, but lower energy density.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Its working principle and cell construction are similar, but use sodium instead of lithium as the intercalating ion.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Sodium–sulfur batteries can operate safely at high temperatures.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Notable sodium battery producers with high safety claims include (non-exclusive) Altris AB, SgNaPlus and Tiamat.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] The largest BESS utilizing sodium-ion technology started operating in 2024 in Hubei province, boasts a capacity of 50 MW / 100 MWh.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] In 2026, CATL unveiled its modular TENER Sodium Energy Storage System, which offers 30 MWh storage capacity.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] It can deliver power for storage durations of 1, 2, 4, 6, and 8 hours, depending on the application.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] It contracted with HyperStrong for a 60 gwh system.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Since they do not have any mechanical parts, battery storage power plants offer extremely short control times and start times, as little as 10 ms.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] They can therefore help dampen the fast oscillations that occur when electrical power networks are operated close to their maximum capacity or when grids suffer anomalies.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] These instabilities – fluctuations with periods of as much as 30 seconds – can produce peak swings of such amplitude that they can cause regional blackouts.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Some of the parameters are voltage, frequency and phase.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] A properly sized battery storage power plant can efficiently counteract these oscillations; therefore, applications are found primarily in those regions where electrical power systems are operated at full capacity, leading to a risk of instability.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] However, some batteries have insufficient control systems, failing during moderate disruptions they should have tolerated.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Batteries are also commonly used for peak shaving for periods of up to a few hours.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] A more recent use is strengthening transmission, as long power lines can be operated closer to their capacity when batteries handle the local difference between supply and demand.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Storage plants can also be used in combination with an intermittent renewable energy source in stand-alone power systems.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] By 2025, global grid battery power capacity was 267 GW with 610 GWh energy capacity, compared to the other major form of grid storage, pumped-storage hydroelectricity with 200 GW power and 9000 GWh energy storage worldwide as of 2025 according to International Hydropower Association.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] The battery market had thus surpassed the power generation capacity of pumped-storage, but remained far smaller in terms of energy capacity.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Relative to 2010, batteries and photovoltaics have followed roughly the same downward price curve due to experience curve effects.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Cells are the major cost component, costing 30-40% of a full system.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Batteries' rapid increase occurred as price drops, with over 100 GW added (mostly LFP) in 2025, up from 10 GW in 2021.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] In 2025, solar power added was down to 6 times bigger than battery power added, as battery increased much faster than solar.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Average world system price was around $120/kWh in 2025.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] The amount of batteries and their associated operational money flow became an investible asset class by 2026, pooling several separate batteries into centrally controlled portfolios.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] This allows small developers with low funds to partner with groups of institutional investors without practical knowledge of the electricity business, to the benefit of both.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] This is a contrast to the usual single energy company approach of developing, owning and operating an electricity facility.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] By mid-2025, China passed 100 GW batteries (164 GW total storage) and added capacity market payments.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] As of May 2025, China’s cumulative BESS installations were reported at 106.9 GW and 240.3 GWh, with global battery storage deployment of nearly 9 GWh in April 2025.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] At the end of 2024, China had 62 GW / 141 GWh of battery power stations.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] In 2020, China added 1,557 MW to its battery storage capacity, while storage facilities for photovoltaics projects accounting for 27% of the capacity, to the total 3,269 MW of electrochemical energy storage capacity.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] The United States installed 57.6 GWh in 2025, and 12.3 GW / 37.1 GWh of batteries in 2024.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] USA had 70 GWh production capacity in 2025, roughly corresponding to domestic market size.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] In 2022, US capacity doubled to 9 GW / 25 GWh.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] At the end of 2021, the capacity grew to 4,588 MW.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] The 2021 price of a 60 MW / 240 MWh (4-hour) battery installation in the United States was US$379/usable kWh, or US$292/nameplate kWh, a 13% drop from 2020.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] In 2010, the United States had 59 MW of battery storage capacity from 7 battery power plants.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] This increased to 49 plants comprising 351 MW of capacity in 2015.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] In 2018, the capacity was 869 MW from 125 plants, capable of storing a maximum of 1,236 MWh of generated electricity.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] By the end of 2020, the battery storage capacity reached 1,756 MW.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] The US market for storage power plants in 2015 increased by 243% compared to 2014.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] In June 2024 the capacity was 4.6 GW of power and 5.9 GWh of energy in the United Kingdom.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] In 2022, UK capacity grew by 800 MWh, ending at 2.4 GW / 2.6 GWh.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] As of May 2021, 1.3 GW of battery storage was operating, with 16 GW of projects in the pipeline potentially deployable over the next few years.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] As of the end of 2024, Europe had reached 61 GWh of installed battery energy storage capacity, after adding 21 GWh that year.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Germany and Italy each contributed approximately 6 GWh to this growth.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] The average installation cost during 2024 ranged between €300 and €400 per kilowatt-hour.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] By comparison, Europe deployed 1.9 GW of new battery capacity in 2022.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Japan’s energy sector has also undergone significant growth in renewable energy capacity. expanding by over 30% within five years, which has contributed to a sharp increase in demand for battery energy storage systems (BESS).
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] More than half of the 2.4 GW of BESS capacity awarded in recent long-term low-carbon power auctions was allocated to foreign-owned companies or consortia.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Projects approved in 2024 alone comprise more than 1.37 GW of power capacity and over 6.7 GWh of energy capacity.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] The country’s Long-Term Decarbonization Power Source Auction supports BESS deployment by guaranteeing fixed cost recovery over a 20-year period.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] However, constraints such as limited price volatility and a price floor in Japan’s power market may limit investment returns for storage operators, signaling the need for further regulatory reform.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Worldwide in 2024, suppliers CRRC had 8% market share, Sungrow 14%, and Tesla Energy 15%.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Some developers are also utilizing retired electric vehicle batteries to build second-life storage systems, with costs potentially 50% lower than those of new battery installations.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Nonetheless, due to the declining cost of new batteries, buyers of second-life systems may only be willing to pay around 10% of the original cost.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] In 2024, a 53 MWh battery storage facility built from approximately 900 used electric vehicle batteries was commissioned in Texas.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] The major 2025 Iberian Peninsula blackout severed the Iberian grid from the rest of Europe on 28 April and then collapsed to a complete blackout in just five seconds, then caused some deaths plus economic losses estimated at up to €4.5 billion.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] The importance of system resilience has become increasingly prominent in Spain.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Battery Energy Storage Systems were at a very low level at around 20 MW, but are now regarded as a key pillar of the Spanish energy transition.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Major utilities such as Iberdrola and Solaria are now actively developing hybrid solar-plus-storage projects to mitigate the impact of solar overproduction and declining market prices.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] Solaria alone has launched eight new BESS installations in Castilla y León and Castilla-La Mancha.
[src:battery-storage-grid/battery-storage-power-station] By April 2026, Spain had 193 MW of grid batteries, and 339 MWh of home batteries, with more in projects.
[src:battery-storage-grid/depth-of-discharge] 2. the fraction of the battery's capacity which is *currently* removed from the battery with regard to its (fully) charged state.
[src:battery-storage-grid/depth-of-discharge] For fully charged batteries, the depth of discharge is connected to the state of charge by the simple formula $\mathrm {DoD} =1-\mathrm {SoC}$ .
[src:battery-storage-grid/depth-of-discharge] The depth of discharge then is the complement of state of charge: as one increases, the other decreases.
[src:battery-storage-grid/depth-of-discharge] This definition is mostly found in scientific sources.
[src:battery-storage-grid/depth-of-discharge] The depth of discharge can therefore (1) refer to the size of the range usually used for discharge or (2) the *current* amount of charge or fraction of the capacity removed from the battery.
[src:battery-storage-grid/depth-of-discharge] To avoid confusion, the exact meaning of DoD should be clear for a given context.
[src:battery-storage-grid/depth-of-discharge] Also, for both definitions, it remains undefined, whether a charged battery's SoC is 100 % or another value.
[src:battery-storage-grid/depth-of-discharge] This reference value is needed to fully describe (1) the *upper and lower limit* of absolute SoC used for operation or (2) the *current value* of the absolute SoC.
[src:battery-storage-grid/depth-of-discharge] During their use, secondary batteries are repeatedly charged and discharged within a certain range of state of charge.
[src:battery-storage-grid/depth-of-discharge] For many battery types, it is beneficial or even mandatory for safety reasons, to not encounter overcharging and/or deep discharge.
[src:battery-storage-grid/depth-of-discharge] To prevent adverse effects, a battery management system or battery charger may keep the battery from extreme levels regarding SoC, thereby limiting the SoC to a reduced range between 0 % and 100 % and decreasing *depth of discharge* below 100 % (see example below).
[src:battery-storage-grid/depth-of-discharge] This corresponds to the DoD in the sense of definition (1).
[src:battery-storage-grid/depth-of-discharge] For almost all known rechargeable battery technologies, such as lead-acid batteries of all kinds like AGM, there is a correlation between the depth of discharge and the cycle life of the battery.
[src:battery-storage-grid/depth-of-discharge] For LiFePO 4 batteries, for example, the state of charge is often limited to the range between 15 % and 85 % to greatly increase their cycle life, resulting in a DoD of 70 %.
[src:battery-storage-grid/depth-of-discharge] While the state of charge is usually expressed using percentage points (0 % = empty; 100 % = full), depth of discharge is either expressed using units of Ah (e.g. for a 50 Ah battery, 0 Ah is full and 50 Ah is empty) or percentage points (100 % is empty and 0 % is full).
[src:battery-storage-grid/depth-of-discharge] The capacity of a battery may also be higher than its nominal rating.
[src:battery-storage-grid/depth-of-discharge] Thus it is possible for the depth of discharge value to exceed the nominal value (e.g., 55 Ah for a 50 Ah battery, or 110 %).
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] "Ancillary services are all services required by the transmission or distribution system operator to enable them to maintain the integrity and stability of the transmission or distribution system as well as the power quality".
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] Ancillary services are specialty services and functions provided by actors within the electric grid that facilitate and support the continuous flow of electricity, so that the demand for electrical energy is met in real time.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] The term ancillary services is used to refer to a variety of operations beyond generation and transmission that are required to maintain grid stability and security.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] These services generally include active power control or frequency control and reactive power control or voltage control, on various timescales.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] Traditionally, ancillary services have been provided by large production units such as synchronous generators.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] With the integration of more intermittent generation and the development of smart grid technologies, the provision of ancillary services is extended to smaller distributed generation and consumption units.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] Electricity frequency is directly connected to the balance of consumption and generation of active power ( $\Delta P=P_{generation}-P_{consume}$ ) and the total rotating energy ( $W_{tot,kin}$ ) of the synchronous power system.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] Where S is the total exchange of active power for the entire grid and H is the normalized inertia constant for the system.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] A system with a small amount of total rotating kinetic energy will be more sensitive to deviations in $\Delta P$ , as the frequency's derivative will be more significantly affected.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] As the total inertia of synchronous grids decreases due to the increasing integration of renewable generation sources, the methodologies and requirements for enabling converter-based generation units to control grid frequency with greater speed and precision are becoming more important.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] Frequency control refers to the need to ensure that the grid frequency stays within a specific range of the nominal frequency.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] Mismatch between electricity generation and demand causes variations in frequency, so control services are required to bring the frequency back to its nominal value and ensure it does not vary out of range.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] where Pm is the change in power of the system.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] If we have multiple generators, each might have its own R.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] This simple equation can be rearranged to find the change in power that corresponds to a given change in frequency.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] Consumer loads expect voltage within a certain range, and the regulators require it be within a certain percent of the nominal voltage (for example, in the US it is ±5%).
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] Reactive power can be used to compensate the voltage drops, but must be provided closer to the loads than real power needs (this is because reactive power tend to travel badly through the grid).
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] Notice that voltage can be controlled also using transformer taps and voltage regulators.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] Scheduling and dispatch are necessary because in most electrical systems energy storage is nearly zero, so at any instant, the power into the system (produced by a generator) must equal the power out of the system (demand from consumers).
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] Since production must so closely match demand, careful scheduling and dispatch are necessary.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] Usually performed by the independent system operator or transmission system operator, both are services dedicated to the commitment and coordination of the generation and transmission units in order to maintain the reliability of the power grid.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] Scheduling refers to before-the-fact actions (like scheduling a generator to produce a certain amount of power the next week), while dispatch refers to the real-time control of the available resources.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] Since production and demand must match so perfectly (see Scheduling and dispatch), operating reserves help make up the difference when production is too low.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] An operating reserve is a generator that can quickly be dispatched to ensure that there is sufficient energy generation to meet load.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] Spinning reserves are generators that are already online and can rapidly increase their power output to meet fast changes in demand.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] Spinning reserves are required because demand can vary on short timescales and rapid response is needed.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] Other operating reserves are generators that can be dispatched by the operator to meet demand, but that cannot respond as quickly as spinning reserves, and grid battery storage that can respond within tens of milliseconds, generally faster than even spinning reserve.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] The grid integration of renewable generation simultaneously requires additional ancillary services and has the potential to provide ancillary services to the grid.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] The inverters that are installed with distributed generation systems and roof top solar systems have the potential to provide many of the ancillary services that are traditionally provided by spinning generators and voltage regulators.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] These services include reactive power compensation, voltage regulation, flicker control, active power filtering and harmonic cancellation.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] Wind turbines with variable-speed generators have the potential to add synthetic inertia to the grid and assist in frequency control.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] CAISO tested the 131 MW Tule wind farm's synchronverter in 2018, and found it could perform some of the grid services similar or better than traditional generators.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] Hydro-Québec began requiring synthetic inertia in 2005 as the first grid operator, demanding a temporary 6% power boost when countering frequency drop by combining the power electronics with the rotational inertia of a wind turbine rotor.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] Similar requirements came into effect in Europe in 2016.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] Plug-in electric vehicles have the potential to be utilized to provide ancillary services to the grid, specifically load regulation and spinning reserves.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] Plug-in electric vehicles can behave like distributed energy storage and have the potential to discharge power back to the grid through bidirectional flow, referred to as vehicle-to-grid (V2G).
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] Plug-in electric vehicles have the ability to supply power at a fast rate which enables them to be used like spinning reserves and provide grid stability with the increased use of intermittent generation such as wind and solar.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] According to the study cited in the reference, which compared the profitability of offering operating reserve ancillary service with the sales of V2G energy from a fleet of vehicles, providing operating reserve regulation service is more profitable than selling V2G energy alone.
[src:battery-storage-grid/frequency-regulation] However, the technologies to utilize electric vehicles to provide ancillary services are not yet widely implemented, but there is much anticipation of their potential.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] As of 2023, the largest form of grid storage is pumped-storage hydroelectricity, with utility-scale batteries and behind-the-meter batteries coming second and third.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Lithium-ion batteries are well suited for short-duration storage (under 8 hours), due to their lower cost and sensitivity to degradation at high states of charge.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Flow batteries and compressed air energy storage may provide storage for medium-duration.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Two forms of storage are suited for long-duration storage: green hydrogen, produced via electrolysis and thermal energy storage.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Energy storage is one option to making grids more flexible.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Another solution is the use of more dispatchable power plants that can change their output rapidly, for instance peaking power plants to fill in supply gaps.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Demand response can shift load to other times and interconnections between regions can balance out fluctuations in renewables production.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] The price of storage technologies typically goes down with experience.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] For instance, lithium-ion batteries have been getting some 20% cheaper for each doubling of worldwide capacity.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Systems with under 40% variable renewables need only short-term storage.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] At 80%, medium-duration storage becomes essential and beyond 90%, long-duration storage does too.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] The economics of long-duration storage is challenging, and alternative flexibility options like demand response may be more economic.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Any electrical power grid must match electricity production to consumption, both of which vary significantly over time.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Energy derived from solar and wind sources varies with the weather on time scales ranging from less than a second to weeks or longer.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Nuclear power is less flexible than fossil fuels, meaning it cannot easily match the variations in demand.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Thus, low-carbon electricity without storage presents special challenges to electric utilities.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Electricity storage is one of the three key ways to replace flexibility from fossil fuels in the grid.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Other options are demand-side response, in which consumers change when they use electricity or how much they use.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] For instance, households may have cheaper night tariffs to encourage them to use electricity at night.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Industry and commercial consumers can also change their demand to meet supply.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Improved network interconnection smooths the variations of renewables production and demand.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] When there is little wind in one location, another might have a surplus of production.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Expansion of transmission lines usually takes a long time.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Energy storage has a large set of roles in the electricity grid and can therefore provide many different services.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] For instance, it can arbitrage by keeping it until the electricity price rises, it can help make the grid more stable, and help reduce investment into transmission infrastructure.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] The type of service provided by storage depends on who manages the technology, whether the technology is based alongside generation of electricity, within the network, or at the side of consumption.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Providing short-term flexibility is a key role for energy storage.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] On the generation side, it can help with the integration of variable renewable energy, storing it when there is an oversupply of wind and solar and electricity prices are low.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] More generally, it can exploit the changes in prices of electricity over time in the wholesale market, charging when electricity is cheap and selling when it is expensive.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] It can further help with grid congestion (where there is insufficient capacity on transmission lines).
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Consumers can use storage to use more of their self-produced electricity (for instance from rooftop solar power).
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Storage can also be used to provide essential grid services.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] On the generation side, storage can smooth out the variations in production, for instance for solar and wind.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] It can assist in a black start after a power outage.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] On the network side, these include frequency regulation (continuously) and frequency response (after unexpected changes in supply or demand).
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] On the consumption side, storage can improve the quality of the delivered electricity in less stable grids.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Investment in storage may make some investments in the transmission and distribution network unnecessary, or may allow them to be scaled down.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Additionally, storage can ensure there is sufficient capacity to meet peak demand within the electricity grid.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Finally, in off-grid home systems or mini-grids, electricity storage can help provide energy access in areas that were previously not connected to the electricity grid.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Recent advances in artificial intelligence and machine learning allow for real-time optimization of energy storage assets.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Reinforcement learning algorithms are being explored to maximize arbitrage, manage degradation, and respond to market signals, particularly in complex and high-renewable systems.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Energy from sunlight or other renewable energy is converted to potential energy for storage in devices such as electric batteries.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] The stored potential energy is later converted to electricity that is added to the power grid, even when the original energy source is not available.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] In daytime, different renewable sources provide different amounts of power to the grid.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] At night, energy is provided by batteries that were charged during the day when renewable energy exceeded customer demand.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Electricity can be stored directly for a short time in capacitors, somewhat longer electrochemically in batteries, and much longer chemically (e.g. hydrogen), mechanically (e.g. pumped hydropower) or as heat.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] The first pumped hydroelectricity was constructed at the end of the 19th century around the Alps in Italy, Austria, and Switzerland.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] The technique rapidly expanded during the 1960s to 1980s nuclear boom, due to nuclear power's inability to quickly adapt to changes in electricity demand.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] In the 21st century, interest in storage surged due to the rise of sustainable energy sources, which are often weather-dependent.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Commercial batteries have been available for over a century.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] However, their widespread use in the power grid is more recent, with only 1 GW available in 2013.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Lithium-ion batteries are the most commonly used batteries for grid applications, as of 2024, following the application of batteries in electric vehicles (EVs).
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] In comparison with EVs, grid batteries require less energy density, meaning that more emphasis can be put on costs, the ability to charge and discharge often and lifespan.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] This has led to a shift towards lithium iron phosphate batteries (LFP batteries), which are cheaper and last longer than traditional lithium-ion batteries.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Costs of batteries are declining rapidly; from 2010 to 2023 costs fell by 90%.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] As of 2024, utility-scale systems account for two thirds of added capacity, and home applications (behind-the-meter) for one third.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Lithium-ion batteries are highly suited to short-duration storage (<8h) due to cost and degradation associated with high states of charge.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] The electric vehicle fleet has a large overall battery capacity, which can potentially be used for grid energy storage.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] This could be in the form of vehicle-to-grid (V2G), where cars store energy when they are not in use, or by repurposing batteries from cars at the end of the vehicle's life.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Car batteries typically range between 33 and 100 kWh; for comparison, a typical upper-middle-class household in Spain might use some 18 kWh in a day.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] By 2030, batteries in electric vehicles may be able to meet all short-term storage demand globally.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] As of 2024, there have been more than 100 V2G pilot projects globally.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] The effect of V2G charging on battery life can be positive or negative.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Increased cycling of batteries can lead to faster degradation, but due to better management of the state of charge and gentler charging and discharging, V2G might instead increase the lifetime of batteries.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Second-hand batteries may be useable for stationary grid storage for roughly 6 years, when their capacity drops from roughly 80% to 60% of the initial capacity.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] LFP batteries are particularly suitable for reusing, as they degrade less than other lithium-ion batteries and recycling is less attractive as their materials are not as valuable.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] In redox flow batteries, energy is stored in liquids, which are placed in two separate tanks.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] When charging or discharging, the liquids are pumped into a cell with the electrodes.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] The amount of energy stored (as set by the size of the tanks) can be adjusted separately from the power output (as set by the speed of the pumps).
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Flow batteries have the advantages of low capital cost for charge-discharge duration over 4 h, and of long durability (many years).
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Flow batteries are inferior to lithium-ion batteries in terms of energy efficiency, averaging efficiencies between 60% and 75%.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Vanadium redox batteries is most commercially advanced type of flow battery, with roughly 40 companies making them as of 2022.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Sodium-ion batteries are a possible alternative to lithium-ion batteries, as they are less flammable, and use cheaper and less critical materials.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] They have a lower energy density, and possibly a shorter lifespan.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] If produced at the same scale as lithium-ion batteries, they may become 20% to 30% cheaper.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Iron-air batteries may be suitable for even longer duration storage than flow batteries (weeks), but the technology is not yet mature.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Storage in supercapacitors works well for applications where a lot of power is needed for short amount of time.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] In the power grid, they are therefore mostly used in short-term frequency regulation.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Various power-to-gas and power-to-fuel technologies exist that can convert excess electricity into an easier to store chemical.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] The lowest cost and most efficient one is hydrogen.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] However, it is easier to use synthetic methane with existing infrastructure and appliances, as it is very similar to natural gas.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] As of 2024, there have been a number of demonstration plants where hydrogen is burned in gas turbines, either co-firing with natural gas, or on its own.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Similarly, a number of coal plants have demonstrated it is possible to co-fire ammonia when burning coal.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] In 2022, there was also a small pilot to burn pure ammonia in a gas turbine.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] A portion of existing gas turbines are capable of co-firing hydrogen, which means there is, as a lower estimate, 80 GW of capacity ready to burn hydrogen.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Hydrogen can be used as a long-term storage medium.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Green hydrogen is produced from the electrolysis of water and converted back into electricity in an internal combustion engine, or a fuel cell, with a round-trip efficiency of roughly 41%.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Together with thermal storage, it is expected to be best suited to seasonal energy storage.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Hydrogen can be stored aboveground in tanks or underground in larger quantities.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Underground storage is easiest in salt caverns, but only a certain number of places have suitable geology.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Storage in porous rocks, for instance in empty gas fields and some aquifers, can store hydrogen at a larger scale, but this type of storage may have some drawbacks.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] For instance, some of the hydrogen can leak or react to form hydrogen sulfide (H₂S) or methane.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Hydrogen can be converted into ammonia in a reaction with nitrogen in the Haber-Bosch process.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Ammonia, a gas at room temperature, is more expensive to produce than hydrogen.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] However, it can be stored more cheaply than hydrogen.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Tank storage is usually done at between one and ten times atmospheric pressure and at a temperature of −30 °C (−22 °F), in liquid form.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Ammonia has multiple uses besides being an energy carrier: it is the basis for the production of many chemicals; the most common use is for fertilizer.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] It can be used for power generation directly, or converted back to hydrogen first.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Alternatively, it has potential applications as a fuel in shipping.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] It is possible to further convert hydrogen into methane via the Sabatier reaction, a chemical reaction which combines CO2 and H2.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] While the reaction that converts CO from gasified coal into CH4 is mature, the process to form methane out of CO2 is less so.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Efficiencies of around 80% one-way can be achieved, that is, some 20% of the energy in hydrogen is lost in the reaction.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Flywheels store energy in the form of mechanical energy.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] They are suited to supplying high levels of electricity over minutes and can also be charged rapidly.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] They have a long lifetime and can be used in settings with widely varying temperatures.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] The technology is mature, but more expensive than batteries and supercapacitors and not used frequently.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] As of 2023, pumped-storage hydroelectricity (PSH) was the largest form of grid energy storage globally, with an installed capacity of 181 GW, surpassing the combined capacity of utility-scale and behind-the-meter battery storage, which totaled approximately 88 GW.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] PSH is particularly effective for managing daily fluctuations in energy demand.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] During periods of low demand, water is pumped to a higher-elevation reservoir, and during peak demand, the stored water is released to generate electricity through turbines.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] The system has an efficiency rate of 75% to 85% and can quickly respond to changes in demand, typically within seconds to minutes.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] While traditional PSH systems require specific geographical conditions, alternative designs have been proposed.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] These include using deep salt caverns or constructing hollow structures on the seabed, where the ocean serves as the upper reservoir.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] However, PSH construction is often expensive, time-consuming, and can have significant environmental and social impacts on nearby communities.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Installing floating solar panels on reservoirs, can increase the efficiency of PSH systems.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] These panels reduce water evaporation and benefit from cooling by the water surface, which also improves their energy generation efficiency.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Hydroelectric dams with large reservoirs can also be operated to provide peak generation at times of peak demand.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Water is stored in the reservoir during periods of low demand and released through the plant when demand is higher.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] While technically no electricity is stored, the net effect is similar to that of pumped storage.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Hydroelectric dams typically offer more storage capacity than dedicated pumped-storage systems.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Upgrades may be needed so that these dams can respond to variable demand.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] For instance, additional investment may be needed in transmission lines, or additional turbines may need to be installed to increase the peak output from the dam.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] As well as energy generation, they often play a role in flood defense and protection of ecosystems, recreation, and they supply water for irrigation.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] This means it is not always possible to change their operation much, but even with low flexibility, they may still play an important role in responding to changes in wind and solar production.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Alternative methods that use gravity include storing energy by moving large solid masses upward against gravity.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] This can be achieved inside old mine shafts or in specially constructed towers where heavy weights are winched up to store energy and allowed a controlled descent to release it.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Compressed air energy storage (CAES) stores electricity by compressing air.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] The compressed air is typically stored in large underground caverns.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] The expanding air can be used to drive turbines, converting the energy back into electricity.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] As air cools when expanding, some heat needs to be added in this stage to prevent freezing.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] This can be provided by a low-carbon source, or in the case of advanced CAES, by reusing the heat that is released when air is compressed.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] As of 2023, there are three advanced CAES projects in operation in China.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Typical efficiencies of advanced CAES are between 60% and 80%.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Another electricity storage method is to compress and cool air, turning it into liquid air, which can be stored and expanded when needed, turning a turbine to generate electricity.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] This is called liquid air energy storage (LAES).
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] The air would be cooled to temperatures of −196 °C (−320.8 °F) to become liquid.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Like with compressed air, heat is needed for the expansion step.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] In the case of LAES, low-grade industrial heat can be used for this.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Energy efficiency for LAES lies between 50% and 70%.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] As of 2023, LAES is moving from pre-commercial to commercial.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] An alternative is the compression of CO 2 to store electricity.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Electricity can be directly stored thermally with a Carnot battery.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] A Carnot battery is a type of energy storage system that stores electricity in heat storage and converts the stored heat back to electricity via thermodynamic cycles (for instance, a turbine).
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] While less efficient than pumped hydro or battery storage, this type of system is expected to be cheap and can provide long-duration storage.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] A pumped-heat electricity storage system is a Carnot battery that uses a reversible heat pump to convert the electricity into heat.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] It usually stores the energy in both a hot and cold reservoir.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] To achieve decent efficiencies (>50%), the temperature ratio between the two must reach a factor of 5.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Thermal energy storage is also used in combination with concentrated solar power (CSP).
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] In CSP, solar energy is first converted into heat, and then either directly converted into electricity or first stored.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] The energy is released when there is little or no sunshine.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] This means that CSP can be used as a dispatchable (flexible) form of generation.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] The energy in a CSP system can for instance be stored in molten salts or in a solid medium such as sand.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Finally, heating and cooling systems in buildings can be controlled to store thermal energy in either the building's mass or dedicated thermal storage tanks.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] This thermal storage can provide load-shifting or even more complex ancillary services by increasing power consumption (charging the storage) during off-peak times and lowering power consumption (discharging the storage) during higher-priced peak times.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] The levelized cost of storing electricity (LCOS) is a measure of the lifetime costs of storing electricity per MWh of electricity discharged.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] It includes investment costs, but also operational costs and charging costs.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] It depends highly on storage type and purpose; as subsecond-scale frequency regulation, minute/hour-scale peaker plants, or day/week-scale season storage.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] For power applications (for instance around ancillary services or black starts), a similar metric is the annuitized capacity cost (ACC), which measures the lifetime costs per kW.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] ACC is lowest when there are few cycles (<300) and when the discharge is less than one hour.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] This is because the technology is reimbursed only when it provides spare capacity, not when it is discharged.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] The cost of storage is coming down following technology-dependent experience curves, the price drop for each doubling in cumulative capacity (or experience).
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Lithium-ion battery prices fall rapidly: the price utilities pay for them falls 19% with each doubling of capacity.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Hydrogen production via electrolysis has a similar learning rate, but it is much more uncertain.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Vanadium-flow batteries typically get 14% cheaper for each doubling of capacity.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Pumped hydropower has not seen prices fall much with increased experience.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Before 2020, most value for storage was in providing power quality services.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Arbitrage is the service with the largest economic potential for storage applications.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] In systems with under 40% of variable renewables, only short-term storage (of less than 4 hours) is needed for integration.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] When the share of variable renewables climbs to 80%, medium-duration storage (between 4 and 16 hours, for instance compressed air) is needed.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Above 90%, large-scale long-duration storage is required.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] The economics of long-duration storage is challenging even then, as the costs are high.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Alternative flexibility options, such as demand response, network expansions or flexible generation (geothermal or fossil gas with carbon capture and storage) may be lower-cost.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Like with renewables, storage will "cannibalise" its own income, but even more strongly.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] That is, with more storage on the market, there is less of an opportunity to do arbitrage or deliver other services to the grid.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] How markets are designed impacts revenue potential too.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] The income from arbitrage is quite variable between years, whereas markets that have capacity payments likely show less volatility.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Electricity storage is not 100% efficient, so more electricity needs to be bought than can be sold.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] This implies that if there is only a small variation in price, it may not be economical to charge and discharge.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] For instance, if the storage application is 75% efficient, the price at which the electricity is sold needs to be at least 1.33 higher than the price for which it was bought.
[src:battery-storage-grid/grid-energy-storage] Typically, electricity prices vary most between day and night, which means that storage up to 8 hours has relatively high potential for profit.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] A **lithium-ion battery** or **Li-ion battery** is a type of rechargeable battery that uses the reversible intercalation of Li+ ions into electronically conducting solids to store energy.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] There are many different varieties, which are usually categorized by the materials used in the cathode.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Compared to other types of rechargeable batteries, they generally have higher specific energy, energy density, and energy efficiency and a longer cycle life and calendar life.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In the three decades since Li-ion batteries were first sold in 1991, their volumetric energy density increased threefold while their cost dropped tenfold.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In late 2024, global demand passed 1 terawatt-hour per year, while production capacity was more than twice that.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The invention and commercialization of Li-ion batteries has had a large impact on technology, as recognized by the 2019 Nobel Prize in Chemistry, which was awarded to contributors to the development of Li-ion batteries.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Li-ion batteries have enabled portable consumer electronics, laptop computers, cellular phones, and electric cars.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] They are used for grid-scale energy storage and in military and aerospace applications.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Li-ion battery sizes are generally not standardised (e.g. in the spirit of the AA battery) and they come in various and unique form factors depending on device and vendor.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] They typically have a nominal voltage of 3.6 or 3.7 V.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Stanley Whittingham conceived intercalation electrodes in the 1970s and created the first rechargeable lithium-ion battery, based on a titanium disulfide cathode and a lithium-aluminium anode, although it suffered from safety problems and was never commercialized.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] John Goodenough expanded on this work in 1980 by using lithium cobalt oxide as a cathode.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The first prototype of the modern Li-ion battery, which uses a carbonaceous anode rather than lithium metal, was developed by Akira Yoshino in 1985 and commercialized by a Sony and Asahi Kasei team led by Yoshio Nishi in 1991.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Whittingham, Goodenough, and Yoshino were awarded the 2019 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for their contributions to the development of lithium-ion batteries.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion batteries can be a fire or explosion hazard as they contain flammable electrolytes.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Progress has been made in the development and manufacturing of safer lithium-ion batteries.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion solid-state batteries are being developed to eliminate the flammable electrolyte.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium and other minerals can have significant issues in mining, with lithium being water intensive in often arid regions and other minerals used in some Li-ion chemistries potentially being conflict minerals such as cobalt.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Environmental issues have encouraged some researchers to improve mineral efficiency and find alternatives such as lithium iron phosphate lithium-ion chemistries or non-lithium-based battery chemistries such as sodium-ion and iron-air batteries.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion cells can be manufactured to optimize energy density or power density.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Handheld electronics mostly use lithium polymer batteries (with a polymer gel as an electrolyte), a lithium cobalt oxide (LiCoO 2) cathode material, and a graphite anode, which together offer high energy density.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium iron phosphate (LiFePO 4), lithium manganese oxide (LiMn 2O 4 spinel, or Li 2MnO 3-based lithium-rich layered materials, LMR-NMC), and lithium nickel manganese cobalt oxide (LiNiMnCoO 2 or NMC) may offer longer life and a higher discharge rate.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] NMC and its derivatives are widely used in the electrification of transport, one of the main technologies (combined with renewable energy) for reducing greenhouse gas emissions from vehicles.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium nickel cobalt aluminum oxide (NCA) is another high-energy lithium-ion chemistry commonly used in electric vehicle batteries.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] One of the earliest examples of research into lithium-ion batteries is a CuF 2/Li battery developed by NASA in 1965.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The breakthrough that produced the earliest form of the modern Li-ion battery was made by British chemist M.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Stanley Whittingham in 1974, who first used titanium disulfide (TiS 2) as a cathode material, which has a layered structure that can take in lithium ions without significant changes to its crystal structure.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Exxon tried to commercialize this battery in the late 1970s, but found the synthesis expensive and complex, as TiS 2 is sensitive to moisture and releases toxic hydrogen sulfide (H 2S) gas on contact with water.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] More prohibitively, the batteries were also prone to spontaneously catch fire due to the presence of metallic lithium in the cells.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] For this, and other reasons, Exxon discontinued the development of Whittingham's lithium-titanium disulfide battery.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In 1980, working in separate groups Ned A.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Godshall et al., and, shortly thereafter, Koichi Mizushima and John B.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Goodenough, after testing a range of alternative materials, replaced TiS 2 with lithium cobalt oxide (LiCoO 2, or LCO), which has a similar layered structure but offers a higher voltage and is much more stable in air.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] This material would later be used in the first commercial Li-ion battery, although it did not, on its own, resolve the persistent issue of flammability.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] These early attempts to develop rechargeable Li-ion batteries used lithium metal anodes, which were ultimately abandoned due to safety concerns, as lithium metal is unstable and prone to dendrite formation, which can cause short-circuiting.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The eventual solution was to use an intercalation anode, similar to that used for the cathode, which prevents the formation of lithium metal during battery charging.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The first to demonstrate lithium ion reversible intercalation into graphite anodes was Jürgen Otto Besenhard in 1974.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Besenhard used organic solvents such as carbonates, however these solvents decomposed rapidly providing short battery cycle life.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Later, in 1980, Rachid Yazami used a solid organic electrolyte, polyethylene oxide, which was more stable.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In 1985, Akira Yoshino at Asahi Kasei Corporation discovered that petroleum coke, a less graphitized form of carbon, can reversibly intercalate Li-ions at a low potential of ~0.5 V relative to Li+ /Li without structural degradation.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Its structural stability originates from its amorphous carbon regions, which serve as covalent joints to pin the layers together.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Although it has a lower capacity compared to graphite (~Li0.5C6, 186 mAh g–1), it became the first commercial intercalation anode for Li-ion batteries owing to its cycling stability.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In 1987, Yoshino patented what would become the first commercial lithium-ion battery using this anode.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] He used Goodenough's previously reported LiCoO2 as the cathode and a carbonate ester-based electrolyte.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The battery was assembled in the discharged state, which made it safer and cheaper to manufacture.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In 1991, using Yoshino's design, Sony began producing and selling the world's first rechargeable lithium-ion batteries.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The following year, a joint venture between Toshiba and Asahi Kasei Co. also released a lithium-ion battery.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Significant improvements in energy density were achieved in the 1990s by replacing Yoshino's soft carbon anode first with hard carbon and later with graphite.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In 1990, Jeff Dahn and two colleagues at Dalhousie University (Canada) reported reversible intercalation of lithium ions into graphite in the presence of ethylene carbonate solvent (which is solid at room temperature and is mixed with other solvents to make a liquid).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] This represented the final innovation of the era that created the basic design of the modern lithium-ion battery.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In 2010, global lithium-ion battery production capacity was 20 gigawatt-hours.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] By 2016, it was 28 GWh, with 16.4 GWh in China.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Global production capacity was 767 GWh in 2020, with China accounting for 75%.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Production in 2021 is estimated by various sources to be between 200 and 600 GWh, and predictions for 2023 range from 400 to 1,100 GWh.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Goodenough, Rachid Yazami and Akira Yoshino received the 2012 IEEE Medal for Environmental and Safety Technologies for developing the lithium-ion battery; Goodenough, Whittingham, and Yoshino were awarded the 2019 Nobel Prize in Chemistry "for the development of lithium-ion batteries".
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Jeff Dahn received the ECS Battery Division Technology Award (2011) and the Yeager award from the International Battery Materials Association (2016).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion batteries are constructed of several key components, including an anode, cathode, separator, casing, electrolyte, and a pair of current collectors.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Typically, the negative electrode of a conventional lithium-ion cell is made from graphite.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The positive electrode is typically a metal oxide or phosphate.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The electrolyte is a lithium salt in an organic solvent.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The negative electrode (which is the anode when the cell is discharging) and the positive electrode (which is the cathode when discharging) are prevented from shorting by a separator.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The electrodes are connected to the powered circuit through two pieces of metal called current collectors.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The negative and positive electrodes swap their electrochemical roles (anode and cathode) when the cell is charged.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Despite this, in discussions of battery design the negative electrode of a rechargeable cell is often just called "the anode" and the positive electrode "the cathode".
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In its fully lithiated state of LiC6, graphite correlates to a theoretical capacity of 1339 coulombs per gram (372 mAh/g).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The positive electrode is generally one of three materials: a layered oxide (such as lithium cobalt oxide), a polyanion (such as lithium iron phosphate) or a spinel (such as lithium manganese oxide).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] More experimental materials include graphene-containing electrodes, although these remain far from commercially viable due to their high cost.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium reacts vigorously with water to form lithium hydroxide (LiOH) and hydrogen gas.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Thus, a non-aqueous electrolyte is typically used, and a sealed container rigidly excludes moisture from the battery pack.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The non-aqueous electrolyte is typically a mixture of organic carbonates such as ethylene carbonate and propylene carbonate containing complexes of lithium ions.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Ethylene carbonate is essential for making solid electrolyte interphase on the carbon anode, but since it is solid at room temperature, a liquid solvent (such as propylene carbonate or diethyl carbonate) is added.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The electrolyte salt is almost always lithium hexafluorophosphate (LiPF 6), which combines good ionic conductivity with chemical and electrochemical stability.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The hexafluorophosphate anion is essential for passivating the aluminium current collector used for the positive electrode.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] A titanium tab is ultrasonically welded to the aluminium current collector.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Copper (with a spot-welded nickel tab) is used as the current collector at the negative electrode.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Current collector design and surface treatments may take various forms: foil, mesh, foam (dealloyed), etched (wholly or selectively), and coated (with various materials) to improve electrical characteristics.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Depending on materials choices, the voltage, energy density, life, and safety of a lithium-ion cell can change dramatically.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Current effort has been exploring the use of novel architectures using nanotechnology to improve performance.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Areas of interest include nano-scale electrode materials and alternative electrode structures.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The reactants in the electrochemical reactions in a lithium-ion cell are the materials of the electrodes, both of which are compounds containing lithium atoms.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Although many thousands of different materials have been investigated, only a very small number are commercially usable.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] All commercial Li-ion cells use intercalation compounds as active materials.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The negative electrode is usually graphite, although silicon is often mixed in to increase the capacity.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The electrolyte is usually lithium hexafluorophosphate, dissolved in a mixture of organic carbonates.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] A number of different materials are used for the positive electrode, such as LiCoO2, LiFePO4, and lithium nickel manganese cobalt oxides.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] During cell discharge the negative electrode is the anode and the positive electrode the cathode: electrons flow from the anode to the cathode through the external circuit.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] An oxidation half-reaction at the anode produces positively charged lithium ions and negatively charged electrons.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The oxidation half-reaction may also produce uncharged material that remains at the anode.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium ions move through the electrolyte; electrons move through the external circuit toward the cathode where they recombine with the cathode material in a reduction half-reaction.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The electrolyte provides a conductive medium for lithium ions but does not partake in the electrochemical reaction.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The reactions during discharge lower the chemical potential of the cell, so discharging transfers energy from the cell to wherever the electric current dissipates its energy, mostly in the external circuit.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] During charging these reactions and transports go in the opposite direction: electrons move from the positive electrode to the negative electrode through the external circuit.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] To charge the cell the external circuit has to provide electrical energy.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] This energy is then stored as chemical energy in the cell (with some loss, e. g., due to coulombic efficiency lower than 1).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Both electrodes allow lithium ions to move in and out of their structures with a process called *insertion* (*intercalation*) or *extraction* (*deintercalation*), respectively.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] As the lithium ions "rock" back and forth between the two electrodes, these batteries are also known as "rocking-chair batteries" or "swing batteries" (a term given by some European industries).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The following equations exemplify the chemistry (left to right: discharging, right to left: charging).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The cell's energy is equal to the voltage times the charge.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Each gram of lithium represents Faraday's constant/6.941, or 13,901 coulombs.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] At 3 V, this gives 41.7 kJ per gram of lithium, or 11.6 kWh per kilogram of lithium.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] This is slightly more than the heat of combustion of gasoline; however, lithium-ion batteries as a whole are still significantly heavier per unit of energy due to the additional materials used in production.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Note that the cell voltages involved in these reactions are larger than the potential at which an aqueous solutions would electrolyze.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] During discharge, lithium ions (Li+ ) carry the current within the battery cell from the negative to the positive electrode, through the non-aqueous electrolyte and separator diaphragm.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] During charging, an external electrical power source applies an over-voltage (a voltage greater than the cell's own voltage) to the cell, forcing electrons to flow from the positive to the negative electrode.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The lithium ions also migrate (through the electrolyte) from the positive to the negative electrode where they become embedded in the porous electrode material in a process known as intercalation.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Constant current constant voltage (CC/CV) is the standard method used to charge lithium-ion cells.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] During the constant current phase, the charger applies a constant current to the battery at a steadily increasing voltage.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Once the maximum charging voltage is reached, the charger changes to the constant voltage phase, where the voltage is held steady and the current gradually decreases, until a minimum current threshold is reached.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] If the starting voltage of the cell voltage is too low, a very low charging current is usually used until the voltage reaches a safe level.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] This is sometimes referred to as trickle charging.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] When charging lithium-ion batteries made of multiple cells in series, top-balancing is also often performed.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Failure to follow current and voltage limitations can result in excessive coulombic heating of the battery, and in the case of overcharge to voltages higher than designed can lead to an explosion.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Charging temperature limits for Li-ion are stricter than the operating limits.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion chemistry performs well at elevated temperatures but prolonged exposure to heat reduces battery life.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Li‑ion batteries offer good charging performance at cooler temperatures and may even allow "fast-charging" within a temperature range of 5 to 45 °C (41 to 113 °F).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Charging should be performed within this temperature range.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] At temperatures from 0 to 5 °C charging is possible, but the charge current should be reduced.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] During a low-temperature (under 0 °C) charge, the slight temperature rise above ambient due to the internal cell resistance is beneficial.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] High temperatures during charging may lead to battery degradation and charging at temperatures above 45 °C will degrade battery performance, whereas at lower temperatures the internal resistance of the battery may increase, resulting in slower charging and thus longer charging times.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Batteries gradually self-discharge even if not connected and delivering current.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Li-ion rechargeable batteries have a self-discharge rate typically stated by manufacturers to be 1.5–2% per month.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The rate increases with temperature and state of charge.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] A 2004 study found that for most cycling conditions self-discharge was primarily time-dependent; however, after several months of stand on open circuit or float charge, state-of-charge dependent losses became significant.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The self-discharge rate did not increase monotonically with state-of-charge, but dropped somewhat at intermediate states of charge.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Self-discharge rates may increase as batteries age.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] By 2007, monthly self-discharge rate was estimated at 2% to 3%, and 2–3% by 2016.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] By comparison, the self-discharge rate for NiMH batteries dropped, as of 2017, from up to 30% per month for previously common cells to about 0.08–0.33% per month for low self-discharge NiMH batteries, and is about 10% per month in NiCd batteries.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion batteries may have multiple levels of structure.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Small batteries consist of a single battery cell.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Larger batteries connect cells in parallel into a module and connect modules in series and parallel into a pack.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Multiple packs may be connected in series to increase the voltage.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Batteries may be equipped with temperature sensors, heating/cooling systems, voltage regulator circuits, voltage taps, and charge-state monitors.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] These components address safety risks like overheating and short circuiting.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] On the macrostructral level (length scale 0.1–5 mm) almost all commercial lithium-ion batteries comprise foil current collectors (aluminium for cathode and copper for anode).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Copper is selected for the anode, because lithium does not alloy with it.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Aluminum is used for the cathode, because it passivates in LiPF6 electrolytes.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Cells with a cylindrical shape are made in a characteristic "swiss roll" manner (known as a "jelly roll" in the US), which means it is a single long "sandwich" of the positive electrode, separator, negative electrode, and separator rolled into a single spool.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] One advantage of cylindrical cells is faster production speed.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] One disadvantage can be a large radial temperature gradient at high discharge rates.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The absence of a case gives pouch cells the highest gravimetric energy density; however, many applications require containment to prevent expansion when their state of charge (SOC) level is high, and for general structural stability.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Both rigid plastic and pouch-style cells are sometimes referred to as prismatic cells due to their rectangular shapes.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Three basic battery types are used in 2020s-era electric vehicles: cylindrical cells (e.g., Tesla), prismatic pouch (e.g., from LG), and prismatic can cells (e.g., from LG, Samsung, Panasonic, and others).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion flow batteries have been demonstrated that suspend the cathode or anode material in an aqueous or organic solution.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] As of 2014, the smallest Li-ion cell was pin-shaped with a diameter of 3.5 mm and a weight of 0.6 g, made by Panasonic.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] A coin cell form factor is available for LiCoO2 cells, usually designated with a "LiR" prefix.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The average voltage of LCO (lithium cobalt oxide) chemistry is 3.6 V if made with hard carbon anode and 3.7 V if made with graphite anode.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Comparatively, the latter has a flatter discharge voltage curve.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion batteries are used in a multitude of applications, including consumer electronics, toys, power tools, electric vehicles and backup power in telecommunications applications.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion batteries are also used for grid energy storage.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Some submarines have also been equipped with lithium-ion batteries.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Because lithium-ion batteries can have a variety of positive and negative electrode materials, the energy density and voltage vary accordingly.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The open-circuit voltage is higher than in aqueous batteries (such as lead–acid, nickel–metal hydride and nickel–cadmium).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Internal resistance increases with both cycling and age, although this depends strongly on the voltage and temperature the batteries are stored at.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Rising internal resistance causes the voltage at the terminals to drop under load, which reduces the maximum current draw.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Eventually, increasing resistance will leave the battery in a state such that it can no longer support the normal discharge currents requested of it without unacceptable voltage drop or overheating.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Batteries with a lithium iron phosphate positive and graphite negative electrodes have a nominal open-circuit voltage of 3.2 V and a typical charging voltage of 3.6 V.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium nickel manganese cobalt (NMC) oxide positives with graphite negatives have a 3.7 V nominal voltage with a 4.2 V maximum while charging.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The charging procedure is performed at constant voltage with current-limiting circuitry (i.e., charging with constant current until a voltage of 4.2 V is reached in the cell and continuing with a constant voltage applied until the current drops close to zero).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Typically, the charge is terminated at 3% of the initial charge current.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In the past, lithium-ion batteries could not be fast-charged and needed at least two hours to fully charge.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Current-generation cells can be fully charged in 45 minutes or less.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In 2015 researchers demonstrated a small 600 mAh capacity battery charged to 68 percent capacity in two minutes and a 3,000 mAh battery charged to 48 percent capacity in five minutes.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The latter battery has an energy density of 620 W·h/L.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The device employed heteroatoms bonded to graphite molecules in the anode.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Performance of manufactured batteries has improved over time.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] For example, from 1991 to 2005 the energy capacity per price of lithium-ion batteries improved more than ten-fold, from 0.3 W·h per dollar to over 3 W·h per dollar.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In the period from 2011 to 2017, progress has averaged 7.5% annually.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Overall, between 1991 and 2024, prices for all types of lithium-ion cells (in dollars per kWh) fell approximately 99%.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] From 1991 to 2018, energy density more than tripled.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Efforts to increase energy density contributed significantly to cost reduction.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Energy density can also be increased by improvements in the chemistry of the cell, for instance, by full or partial replacement of graphite with silicon.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Silicon anodes enhanced with graphene nanotubes to eliminate the premature degradation of silicon allow for record-breaking battery energy density of up to 350 Wh/kg and lowering EV prices to be competitive with ICEs.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Differently sized cells of the same format (shape) with the same chemistry may have different energy densities.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Jelly roll cells usually have a higher energy density than coin or prismatic cells of the same Ah, because of a tighter/compresses packing of the cell layers.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Among cylindrical cells, those with a larger size have a larger energy density, albeit the exact value strongly depends on the thickness of the electrode layers.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The disadvantage of large cells is decrease of the heat transfer from the cell to its surroundings.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The table below shows the result of an experimental evaluation of a "high-energy" type 3.0 Ah 18650 NMC cell in 2021, round-trip efficiency which compared the energy going into the cell and energy extracted from the cell from 100% (4.2v) SoC to 0% SoC (cut off 2.0v).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] A round-trip efficiency is the percent of energy that can be used relative to the energy that went into charging the battery.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The lifespan of a lithium-ion battery is typically defined as the number of full charge-discharge cycles to reach a failure threshold in terms of capacity loss or impedance rise.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Manufacturers' datasheets typically uses the word "cycle life" to specify lifespan in terms of the number of cycles to reach 80% of the rated battery capacity.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Simply storing lithium-ion batteries in the charged state also reduces their capacity (the amount of cyclable Li+) and increases the cell resistance (primarily due to the continuous growth of the solid electrolyte interface on the anode).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Calendar life is used to represent the whole life cycle of battery involving both the cycle and inactive storage operations.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Battery cycle life is affected by many different stress factors including temperature, discharge current, charge current, and state of charge ranges (depth of discharge).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Batteries are not fully charged and discharged in real applications such as smartphones, laptops and electric cars and hence defining battery life via full discharge cycles can be misleading.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] To avoid this confusion, researchers sometimes use cumulative discharge defined as the total amount of charge (Ah) delivered by the battery during its entire life or equivalent full cycles, which represents the summation of the partial cycles as fractions of a full charge-discharge cycle.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Battery degradation during storage is affected by temperature and battery state of charge (SOC) and a combination of full charge (100% SOC) and high temperature (usually > 50 °C) can result in a sharp capacity drop and gas generation.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Multiplying the battery cumulative discharge by the rated nominal voltage gives the total energy delivered over the life of the battery.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] From this one can calculate the cost per kWh of the energy (including the cost of charging).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Over their lifespan, batteries degrade gradually leading to reduced cyclable charge (a.k.a.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Ah capacity) and increased resistance (the latter translates into a lower operating cell voltage).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Also, battery life in room temperature is maximal.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] High charge levels also hasten capacity loss.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Frequent charge to > 90% and discharge to < 10% may also hasten capacity loss.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Keeping the li-ion battery status to about 60% to 80% can reduce the capacity loss.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In a study, scientists provided 3D imaging and model analysis to reveal main causes, mechanics, and potential mitigations of the problematic degradation of the batteries over charge cycles.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium metal plating also results in the loss of lithium inventory (cyclable Ah charge), as well as internal short-circuiting and ignition of a battery.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Once Li plating commences during cycling, it results in larger slopes of capacity loss per cycle and resistance increase per cycle.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] This degradation mechanism become more prominent during fast charging and low temperatures.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Loss of the (negative or positive) electroactive materials due to dissolution (e.g. of Mn3+ species), cracking, exfoliation, detachment or even simple regular volume change during cycling.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] It shows up as both charge and power fade (increased resistance).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Both positive and negative electrode materials are subject to fracturing due to the volumetric strain of repeated (de)lithiation cycles.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Structural degradation of cathode materials, such as Li+/Ni2+ cation mixing in nickel-rich materials.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] This manifests as "electrode saturation", loss of cyclable Ah charge and as a "voltage fade".
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Negative copper current collector is particularly prone to corrosion/dissolution at low cell voltages.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] PVDF binder also degrades, causing the detachment of the electroactive materials, and the loss of cyclable Ah charge.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] These are shown in the figure on the right.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] A change from one main degradation mechanism to another appears as a knee (slope change) in the capacity vs. cycle number plot.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Most studies of lithium-ion battery aging have been done at elevated (50–60 °C) temperatures for accelerated aging.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Under these storage conditions, fully charged nickel-cobalt-aluminum and lithium-iron phosphate cells lose ca.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] 20% of their cyclable charge in 1–2 years.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] It is believed that the aforementioned anode aging is the most important degradation pathway in these cases.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] On the other hand, manganese-based cathodes show a (ca.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] 20–50%) faster degradation under these conditions, probably due to the additional mechanism of Mn ion dissolution.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] At 25 °C the degradation of lithium-ion batteries seems to follow the same pathway(s) as the degradation at 50 °C, but with half the speed.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In other words, based on the limited extrapolated experimental data, lithium-ion batteries are expected to lose irreversibly around 20% of their cyclable charge in 3–5 years or 1000–2000 cycles at 25 °C.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion batteries with titanate anodes do not suffer from SEI growth, and last longer (>5000 cycles) than graphite anodes.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] However, in complete cells other degradation mechanisms (i.e. the dissolution of Mn3+ and the Ni2+/Li+ place exchange, decomposition of PVDF binder and particle detachment) show up after 1000–2000 days, and the use titanate anode does not improve full cell durability in practice.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium plating is a phenomenon in which certain conditions lead to metallic lithium forming and depositing onto the surface of the battery's anode rather than intercalating within the anode material's structure.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Low temperatures, overcharging and high charging rates can exacerbate this occurrence.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] During these conditions, lithium ions may not intercalate uniformly into the anode material and form layers of lithium ion on the surface in the form of dendrites.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] **Lithium dendrites** are tiny needle-like structures that can accumulate and pierce the separator, causing a short circuit can initiate thermal runaway.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] This cascade of rapid and uncontrolled energy can lead to battery swelling, increased heat, fires and or explosions.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Additionally, this dendritic growth can lead to side reactions with the electrolyte and convert the fresh plated lithium into electrochemically inert dead lithium.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Moreover, the dendritic growth brought on by lithium plating can degrade the lithium-ion battery and lead to poor cycling efficiency and safety hazards.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Some ways to mitigate lithium plating and the dendritic growth is by controlling the temperature, optimizing the charging conditions, and improving the materials used.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In terms of temperature, the ideal charging temperature is anywhere between 0 °C to 45 °C, but also room temperature is ideal (20 °C to 25 °C).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Advancements in materials innovation requires much research and development in the electrolyte selection and improving the anode resistance to plating.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] One such materials innovation would be to add other compounds to the electrolyte like fluoroethylene carbonate (FEC) to form a rich LiF SEI.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Another novel method would be to coat the separator in a protective shield that essentially "kills" the lithium ions before it can form these dendrites.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Certain manganese containing cathodes can degrade by the Hunter degradation mechanism resulting in manganese dissolution and reduction on the anode.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] By the Hunter mechanism for LiMn 2O 4, hydrofluoric acid catalyzes the loss of manganese through disproportionation of a surface trivalent manganese to form a tetravalent manganese and a soluble divalent manganese: 2Mn3+ → Mn2++ Mn4+ Material loss of the spinel results in capacity fade.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Temperatures as low as 50 °C initiate Mn2+ deposition on the anode as metallic manganese with the same effects as lithium and copper plating.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Cycling over the theoretical max and min voltage plateaus destroys the crystal lattice via Jahn-Teller distortion, which occurs when Mn4+ is reduced to Mn3+ during discharge.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Storage of a battery charged to greater than 3.6 V initiates electrolyte oxidation by the cathode and induces SEI layer formation on the cathode.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] As with the anode, excessive SEI formation forms an insulator resulting in capacity fade and uneven current distribution.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Storage at less than 2 V results in the slow degradation of LiCoO 2 and LiMn 2O 4 cathodes, the release of oxygen and irreversible capacity loss.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Discharging below 2 V can also result in the dissolution of the copper anode current collector and, thus, in catastrophic internal short-circuiting on recharge.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The IEEE standard 1188–1996 recommends replacing lithium-ion batteries in an electric vehicle, when their charge capacity drops to 80% of the nominal value.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In what follows, we shall use the 20% capacity loss as a comparison point between different studies.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p01] We shall note, nevertheless, that the linear model of degradation (the constant % of charge loss per cycle or per calendar time) is not always applicable, and that a "knee point", observed as a change of the slope, and related to the change of the main degradation mechanism, is often observed.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The problem of lithium-ion battery safety was recognized even before were first commercially released in 1991.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The two main reasons for lithium-ion battery fires and explosions are related to processes on the negative electrode (anode when discharging, cathode when charging).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] During a normal battery charge lithium ions intercalate into graphite.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] However, if the charge is too fast or the temperature is too low lithium metal starts plating on the negative electrode, and the resulting dendrites can penetrate the battery separator, internally short-circuit the cell, and result in high electric current, heating and ignition.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] In other mechanisms, an explosive reaction between the negative electrode material (LiC6) and the solvent (liquid organic carbonate) occurs even at open circuit, provided that the electrode temperature exceeds a certain threshold above 70 °C.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Lithium-ion batteries in the 18650 format or larger may incorporate safety mechanisms such as a current interrupt device (CID) and a positive temperature coefficient (PTC) device.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The CID consists of two metal disks in electrical contact.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] When internal pressure increases, the disks separate, breaking the circuit and terminating the current.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The PTC device is composed of a conductive polymer; an increase in current causes the polymer to heat, increasing its electrical resistance and reducing the current flow.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Lithium-ion batteries can be a safety hazard since they contain a flammable electrolyte and may become pressurized if they become damaged.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] A battery cell charged too quickly could cause a short circuit, leading to overheating, explosions, and fires.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] 4. internal short circuit, e.g. due to manufacturing flaws or aging.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Because of these risks, testing standards are more stringent than those for acid-electrolyte batteries, requiring both a broader range of test conditions and additional battery-specific tests, and there are shipping limitations imposed by safety regulators.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] There have been battery-related recalls by some companies, including the 2016 Samsung Galaxy Note 7 recall for battery fires.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Lithium-ion batteries have a flammable liquid electrolyte.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] A faulty battery can cause a serious fire.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Faulty chargers can affect the safety of the battery because they can destroy the battery's protection circuit.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] While charging at temperatures below 0 °C, the negative electrode of the cells gets plated with pure lithium, which can compromise the safety of the whole pack.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Short-circuiting a battery will cause the cell to overheat and possibly to catch fire.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Smoke from thermal runaway in a Li-ion battery is both flammable and toxic.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Batteries are tested according to the UL 9540A fire standard, and the TS-800 standard also tests fire propagation from one battery container to adjacent containers.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] UPS Airlines Flight 6 crashed in Dubai after its payload of batteries spontaneously ignited.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] To reduce fire hazards, research projects are intended to develop non-flammable electrolytes.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] If a lithium-ion battery is damaged, crushed, or subjected to a higher electrical load without having overcharge protection, problems may arise.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] External short circuit can trigger a battery explosion.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Such incidents can occur when lithium-ion batteries are not disposed of through the appropriate channels, but are thrown away with other waste.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The way they are treated by recycling companies can damage them and cause fires, which in turn can lead to large-scale conflagrations.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Twelve such fires were recorded in Swiss recycling facilities in 2023.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] If overheated or overcharged, Li-ion batteries may suffer thermal runaway and cell rupture.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] During thermal runaway, internal degradation and oxidization processes can keep cell temperatures above 500 °C, with the possibility of igniting secondary combustibles, as well as leading to leakage, explosion or fire in extreme cases.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] To reduce these risks, many lithium-ion cells (and battery packs) contain fail-safe circuitry that disconnects the battery when its voltage is outside the safe range of 3–4.2 V per cell, or when overcharged or discharged.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Lithium battery packs, whether constructed by a vendor or the end-user, without effective battery management circuits are susceptible to these issues.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Poorly designed or implemented battery management circuits also may cause problems; it is difficult to be certain that any particular battery management circuitry is properly implemented.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Lithium-ion cells are susceptible to stress by voltage ranges outside of safe ones between 2.5 and 3.65/4.1/4.2 or 4.35 V (depending on the components of the cell).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Exceeding this voltage range results in premature aging and in safety risks due to the reactive components in the cells.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] When stored for long periods the small current draw of the protection circuitry may drain the battery below its shutoff voltage; normal chargers may then be useless since the battery management system (BMS) may retain a record of this battery (or charger) "failure".
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Many types of lithium-ion cells cannot be charged safely below 0 °C, as this can result in plating of lithium on the anode of the cell, which may cause complications such as internal short-circuit paths.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] These features are required because the negative electrode produces heat during use, while the positive electrode may produce oxygen.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] However, these additional devices occupy space inside the cells, add points of failure, and may irreversibly disable the cell when activated.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Further, these features increase costs compared to nickel metal hydride batteries, which require only a hydrogen/oxygen recombination device and a back-up pressure valve.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Contaminants inside the cells can defeat these safety devices.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Also, these features can not be applied to all kinds of cells, e.g., prismatic high-current cells cannot be equipped with a vent or thermal interrupt.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] High-current cells must not produce excessive heat or oxygen, lest there be a failure, possibly violent.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Instead, they must be equipped with internal thermal fuses which act before the anode and cathode reach their thermal limits.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Replacing the lithium cobalt oxide positive electrode material with a lithium metal phosphate such as lithium iron phosphate (LFP) improves cycle counts, shelf life and safety, but lowers capacity.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] As of 2006, these safer lithium-ion batteries were mainly used in electric cars and other large-capacity battery applications, where safety is critical.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] In 2016, an LFP-based energy storage system was chosen to be installed in Paiyun Lodge on Mt.Jade (Yushan) (the highest lodge in Taiwan).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] As of June 2024, the system was still operating safely.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] In 2006, approximately 10 million Sony batteries used in laptops were recalled, including those in laptops from Dell, Sony, Apple, Lenovo, Panasonic, Toshiba, Hitachi, Fujitsu and Sharp.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The batteries were found to be susceptible to internal contamination by metal particles during manufacture.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Under some circumstances, these particles could pierce the separator, causing a dangerous short circuit.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] IATA estimates that over a billion lithium metal and lithium-ion cells are flown each year.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Some kinds of lithium batteries may be prohibited aboard aircraft because of the fire hazard.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Some postal administrations restrict air shipping (including EMS) of lithium and lithium-ion batteries, either separately or installed in equipment.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] In 2023, most commercial Li-ion batteries employed alkylcarbonate solvents to assure the formation solid electrolyte interface on the negative electrode.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Since such solvents are readily flammable, there has been active research to replace them with non-flammable solvents or to add fire suppressants.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Another source of hazard is hexafluorophosphate anion, which is needed to passivate the negative current collector made of aluminium.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Hexafluorophosphate reacts with water and releases volatile and toxic hydrogen fluoride.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Several strategies have been explored for developing non-flammable Li-ion battery electrolytes.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] One approach uses fluorinated (co-)solvents, such as methyl-(2,2,2-trifluoroethyl)-carbonate (FEMC) or methyl-3,3,3-trifluoropropionate (MTFP).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Another approach uses fluorinated anions, such as lithium bis(trifluoromethanesulfonyl)imide or lithium difluoro(oxalato)borate in high concentrations.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] As of 2021, almost 90% of raw lithium extraction originated from three countries: Australia (53%), Chile (24%), and China (10%), with almost all production coming from China (56%), Chile (32%) and Argentina (11%).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Extraction of lithium, nickel, and cobalt, manufacture of solvents, and mining byproducts present significant environmental and health hazards.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Lithium extraction can be fatal to aquatic life due to water pollution.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] It is known to cause surface water contamination, drinking water contamination, respiratory problems, ecosystem degradation and landscape damage.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] It also leads to unsustainable water consumption in arid regions (1.9 million liters per ton of lithium).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Massive byproduct generation of lithium extraction also presents unsolved problems, such as large amounts of magnesium and lime waste.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Lithium mining takes place in North and South America, Asia, South Africa, Australia, and China.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Cobalt for Li-ion batteries is largely mined in the Congo (see also Mining industry of the Democratic Republic of the Congo).
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Open-pit cobalt mining has led to deforestation and habitat destruction in the Democratic Republic of Congo.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Open-pit nickel mining has led to environmental degradation and pollution in developing countries such as the Philippines and Indonesia.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] In 2024, nickel mining and processing was one of the main causes of deforestation in Indonesia.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Manufacturing a kg of Li-ion battery takes about 67 megajoules (MJ) of energy.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The global warming potential of lithium-ion batteries manufacturing strongly depends on the energy source used in mining and manufacturing operations, and is difficult to estimate, but one 2019 study estimated 73 kg CO2e/kWh.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Effective recycling can reduce the carbon footprint of the production significantly.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The Li-ion battery recycling rate is often misconstrued to be 5%, in reality, insufficient research exists to determine the exact figure.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The European Union estimates 49% of portable batteries sold were collected for recycling in 2023, whilst the UK estimates 45% as of 2026.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] New EU legislation requires 70% of collected Li-ion battery material to be recovered through recycling by 2031, which must include recovery rates of 80% for lithium and 95% for cobalt, nickel, and manganese; however, no recycled lithium has re-entered the EU as of 2023.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] These measures aim to aid sustainability efforts and reduce pressure on raw material extraction, as demand for lithium and cobalt is expected to increase 8-fold by 2040, far exceeding current production capabilities.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Most research focuses on the recovery of active materials, especially lithium which is a critical raw material; however, through advanced recycling techniques and more sustainable design considerations, electrolytes, binders, and separators can also recycled.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Recycling is a multi-step process, starting with the storage of batteries before disposal, followed by manual testing, disassembling, and finally the chemical separation of battery components.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Re-use of the battery is preferred over complete recycling as there is less embodied energy in the process.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] As these batteries are a lot more reactive than classical vehicle waste like tire rubber, there are significant risks to stockpiling used batteries.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The pyrometallurgical method uses a high-temperature furnace to reduce the components of the metal oxides in the battery to an alloy of Co, Cu, Fe, and Ni.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] This is the most common and commercially established method of recycling and can be combined with other similar batteries to increase smelting efficiency and improve thermodynamics.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The metal current collectors aid the smelting process, allowing whole cells or modules to be melted at once.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The product of this method is a collection of metallic alloy, slag, and gas.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] At high temperatures, the polymers used to hold the battery cells together burn off and the metal alloy can be separated through a hydrometallurgical process into its separate components.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The slag can be further refined or used in the cement industry.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The process is relatively risk-free and the exothermic reaction from polymer combustion reduces the required input energy.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] However, in the process, the plastics, electrolytes, and lithium salts will be lost.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] This method involves the use of aqueous solutions to remove the desired metals from the cathode.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The most common reagent is sulfuric acid.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Factors that affect the leaching rate include the concentration of the acid, time, temperature, solid-to-liquid-ratio, and reducing agent.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Once leached, the metals can be extracted through precipitation reactions controlled by changing the pH level of the solution.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Cobalt, the most expensive metal, can then be recovered in the form of sulfate, oxalate, hydroxide, or carbonate.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] More recently, recycling methods experiment with the direct reproduction of the cathode from the leached metals.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] In these procedures, concentrations of the various leached metals are premeasured to match the target cathode and then the cathodes are directly synthesized.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The main issues with this method, however, are the large volume of solvent required and the high cost of neutralization.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Although it is easy to shred up the battery, mixing the cathode and anode at the beginning complicates the process, so they will also need to be separated.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Unfortunately, the current design of batteries makes the process extremely complex and it is difficult to separate the metals in a closed-loop battery system.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Shredding and dissolving may occur at different locations.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Direct recycling is the removal of the cathode or anode from the electrode, which are then reconditioned and reused in a new battery.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Mixed metal-oxides can be added to the new electrode with very little change to the crystal morphology.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The process generally involves the addition of new lithium to replenish the loss of lithium in the cathode due to degradation from cycling.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Cathode strips are obtained from the dismantled batteries, then soaked in NMP, and undergo sonication to remove excess deposits.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] It is treated hydrothermally with a solution containing LiOH/Li2SO4 before annealing.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] This method is extremely cost-effective for noncobalt-based batteries as the raw materials do not make up the bulk of the cost.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Direct recycling avoids the time-consuming and expensive purification steps, which is great for low-cost cathodes such as LiMn2O4 and LiFePO4.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] For these cheaper cathodes, most of the cost, embedded energy, and carbon footprint is associated with the manufacturing rather than the raw material.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] It is experimentally shown that direct recycling can reproduce similar properties to pristine graphite.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The drawback of the method lies in the condition of the retired battery.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] In the case where the battery is relatively healthy, direct recycling can cheaply restore its properties.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] However, for batteries where the state of charge is low, direct recycling may not be worth the investment.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The process must also be tailored to the specific cathode composition, and therefore the process must be configured to one type of battery at a time.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Lastly, in a time with rapidly developing battery technology, the design of a battery today may no longer be desirable a decade from now, rendering direct recycling ineffective.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Physical materials separation recovered materials by mechanical crushing and exploiting physical properties of different components such as particle size, density, ferromagnetism and hydrophobicity.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Copper, aluminum and steel casing can be recovered by sorting.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The remaining materials, called "black mass", which is composed of nickel, cobalt, lithium and manganese, need a secondary treatment to recover.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] For the biological metals reclamation or bio-leaching, the process uses microorganisms to digest metal oxides selectively.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Then, recyclers can reduce these oxides to produce metal nanoparticles.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Although bio-leaching has been used successfully in the mining industry, this process is still nascent to the recycling industry and plenty of opportunities exists for further investigation.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Electrolyte recycling consists of two phases.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The collection phase extracts the electrolyte from the spent Li-ion battery.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] This can be achieved through mechanical processes, distillation, freezing, solvent extraction, and supercritical fluid extraction.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Due to the volatility, flammability, and sensitivity of the electrolyte, the collection process poses a greater difficulty than the collection process for other components of a Li-ion battery.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The next phase consists of separation/electrolyte regeneration.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Separation consists of isolating the individual components of the electrolyte.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] This approach is often used for the direct recovery of the Li salts from the organic solvents.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] In contrast, regeneration of the electrolyte aims to preserve the electrolyte composition by removing impurities which can be achieved through filtration methods.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The recycling of the electrolytes, which consists 10–15 wt.% of the Li-ion battery, provides both economic and environmental benefits.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] These benefits include the recovery of the valuable Li-based salts and the prevention of hazardous compounds, such as volatile organic compounds (VOCs) and carcinogens, being released into the environment.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Compared to electrode recycling, less focus is placed on recycling the electrolyte of Li-ion batteries due to lower economic benefits and greater process challenges.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Such challenges can include the difficulty associated with recycling different electrolyte compositions, removing side products accumulated from electrolyte decomposition during its runtime, and removal of electrolyte adsorbed onto the electrodes.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Due to these challenges, current pyrometallurgical methods of Li-ion battery recycling forgo electrolyte recovery, releasing hazardous gases upon heating.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] However, due to high energy consumption and environmental impact, future recycling methods are being directed away from this approach.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Extraction of raw materials for lithium-ion batteries may present dangers to local people, especially land-based indigenous populations.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Cobalt sourced from the Democratic Republic of the Congo is often mined by workers using hand tools with few safety precautions, resulting in frequent injuries and deaths.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Pollution from these mines has exposed people to toxic chemicals that health officials believe to cause birth defects and breathing difficulties.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Human rights activists have alleged, and investigative journalism reported confirmation, that child labor is used in these mines.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Development of the Thacker Pass lithium mine in Nevada, USA has been met with protests and lawsuits from several indigenous tribes who have said they were not provided free prior and informed consent and that the project threatens cultural and sacred sites.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Links between resource extraction and missing and murdered indigenous women have also prompted local communities to express concerns that the project will create risks to indigenous women.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Protestors have been occupying the site of the proposed mine since January, 2021.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Researchers are actively working to improve the power density, safety, cycle durability (battery life), recharge time, cost, flexibility, and other characteristics, as well as research methods and uses, of these batteries.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Solid-state batteries are being researched as a breakthrough in technological barriers.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Currently, solid-state batteries are expected to be the most promising next-generation battery, and various companies are working to popularize them.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Research areas for lithium-ion batteries include extending lifetime, increasing energy density, improving safety, reducing cost, and increasing charging speed, among others.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Research has been under way in the area of non-flammable electrolytes as a pathway to increased safety based on the flammability and volatility of the organic solvents used in the typical electrolyte.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Strategies include aqueous lithium-ion batteries, ceramic solid electrolytes, polymer electrolytes, ionic liquids, and heavily fluorinated systems.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] One of the ways to improve batteries is to combine the various cathode materials.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] This allows researchers to improve on the qualities of a material, while limiting the negatives.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] One possibility is coating lithium nickel manganese oxide with lithium iron phosphate through resonant acoustic mixing.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The resulting material benefits from an increase electrochemical performance and improved capacity retention.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Similar work was done with iron (III) phosphate.
[src:battery-storage-grid/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Advances in anionic redox understanding have led to stabilization strategies like surface fluorination, improving cycling stability and safety.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] In a battery electric vehicle (BEV), the state of charge indicates the remaining energy in the battery pack.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] The state of charge can help to reduce electrical car owners' anxiety when they are waiting in the line or stay at home since it will reflect the progress of charging and let owners know when it will be ready.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] However on any vehicle dashboard, especially in plug-in hybrid vehicles, the state of charge presented as a gauge or percentage value may not be representative of a real level of charge.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] A noticeable amount of energy may be reserved for hybrid-work operations.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] Examples of such cars are Mitsubishi Outlander PHEV (all versions/years of production), where a charge level of zero is indicated to the driver when the real charge level is 20–22%.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] Another one is the BMW i3 REX (Range Extender version), where about 6% of SoC is reserved for PHEV-alike operations.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] State of charge is also known to impact battery aging.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] To extend battery lifetime, extremes of state of charge should be avoided and reduced variations windows are also preferable.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] Usually, SoC cannot be measured directly but it can be estimated from direct measurement variables in two ways: offline and online.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] In offline techniques, the battery desires to be charged and discharged in constant rate such as Coulomb-counting.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] This method gives precise estimation of battery SoC, but they are protracted, costly, and interrupt main battery performance.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] Therefore, researchers are looking for some online techniques.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] This method works only with batteries that offer access to their liquid electrolyte, such as non-sealed lead acid batteries.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] The specific gravity of the electrolyte can be used to indicate the SoC of the battery.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] Hydrometers are used to calculate the specific gravity of a battery.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] To find specific gravity, it is necessary to measure out volume of the electrolyte and to weigh it.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] Then specific gravity is given by (mass of electrolyte [g]/ volume of electrolyte [ml])/ (Density of Water, i.e.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] To find SoC from specific gravity, a look-up table of SG vs SoC is needed.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] Refractometry has been shown to be a viable method for continuous monitoring of the state of charge.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] The refractive index of the battery electrolyte is directly relatable to the specific gravity or density of the electrolyte of the cell.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] Notably, analysis of electrolyte does not provide information about the state-of-charge in the case of lithium-ion batteries and other batteries, that do not produce or consume solvent or dissolved species during their operation.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] This method converts a reading of the battery voltage to SoC, using the known discharge curve (voltage vs.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] However, the voltage is more significantly affected by the battery current (due to the battery's electrochemical kinetics) and temperature.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] This method can be made more accurate by compensating the voltage reading by a correction term proportional to the battery current, and by using a look-up table of battery's open circuit voltage vs. temperature.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] In fact, it is a stated goal of battery design to provide a voltage as constant as possible no matter the SoC, which makes this method difficult to apply.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] For batteries, that have voltage independent on their state-of-charge (such as lithium iron phosphate battery), open-circuit voltage measurements cannot provide a reliable estimate of the SoC.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] On the other hand, batteries with a sloping voltage-charge curves (such as nickel-cobalt-manganese battery), are more amenable to SoC estimation from the open-circuit voltage measurements.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] This method, also known as *coulomb counting*, calculates the SoC by measuring the battery current and integrating it in time.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] Maxim Integrated touts a combined voltage and charge approach that is claimed superior to either method alone; it is implemented in their ModelGauge m3 series of chips, such as MAX17050, which is used in the Nexus 6 and Nexus 9 Android devices, for example.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] To overcome the shortcomings of the voltage method and the current integration method, a Kalman filter can be used.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] The battery can be described with an electrical model which the Kalman filter will use to predict the over-voltage given the observed current.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] In combination with coulomb counting, it can make an accurate estimation of the state of charge.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] The strength of this technique is that a Kalman filter adjusts its relative trust of the battery voltage and coulomb counting in real time.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] This method can be used with certain NiMH batteries, whose internal pressure increases rapidly when the battery is charged.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] More commonly, a pressure switch indicates if the battery is fully charged.
[src:battery-storage-grid/state-of-charge] This method may be improved by taking into account Peukert's law which is a function of charge/discharge current.
